2.content:
Analyze what apps and users use logs most.

Use filters:
* *User* â€“ see user's query consumption across apps
* *Application* â€“ see query consumption for all users in this app
* *User and application* â€“ see specific user's query consumption for specific app 
* *No filter* â€“ see all users query consumption across apps

4.content: # Query consumption across apps and users

8.title: Queries across Grail log buckets
8.query:
fetch dt.system.query_executions
| filter status == "SUCCEEDED" AND scanned_bytes>0
| fields query_string, status, timestamp, scanned_bytes, bucket = if(bucket == "","empty",else:bucket)
| summarize {volume = count(), sum(scanned_bytes)}, by:(bucket)
| summarize array = collectArray(record(bucket=bucket,volume=volume)),volume=collectArray(volume)
| fieldsAdd sum = arraySum(volume)
| expand array
| lookup [
  fetch dt.system.buckets
],
  sourceField: array[bucket],
  lookupField: name,
  prefix: "buckets.",
  executionOrder:leftFirst
| filter buckets.dt.system.table=="logs"
| fields `bucket` = array[bucket], `volume` = array[volume], percentage = (toDouble(array[volume]/sum) * 100)
| sort percentage desc

| filter dt.system.table == "logs"
| summarize sum(estimated_uncompressed_bytes), by: {name}, alias: size

13.title: Log query volume

19.content:
**This dashboard helps you track log query consumption in your tenant with DPS licensing**.
The consumption data is based on billing events, and query details are based on query execution events.
* Use `Application` and `User` dropdowns to focus on selected field.
* Use the `Price` field to reflect your custom log query price point per gibibyte scanned (list price $0.0035).

20.content:
Validate your bucket segmentation strategy:
* **The pie chart** references total log volume per bucket where logs have been ingested across any timeframe.
* **The donut chart** shows which buckets your users have queried in current  timeframe.
 
ðŸ’¡ **Optimization opportunity**: If most of your queries address a single/default bucket, you could improve query performance and consumption by segmenting data into multiple buckets.

21.content:
Monitor DQL queries fetching logs which don't utilize [best practices](https://docs.dynatrace.com/docs/shortlink/dql-best-practices) for query performance and consumption.

Following queries are missing commands/parameters like `filter`, `scanLimit`, `samplingRatio`, `limit` and have default timeframe.

ðŸ’¡ **Optimization opportunity**: for frequently executed queries, suggest users to filter, limit, or sample data to avoid reoccurring high volume queries

_**Delete this section before sharing with a customer**_

#### Release notes

v0.6
* Replaced code blocks with DQL blocks using multi-select variables for user and app.

v0.5
* Added dashboard IDs to dashboard consumption overview
* Added new tile showing reoccurring queries in classic dashboards (`dynatrace.classic.dashboard-log-tile`) indicative of auto-refresh tiles.

v0.4
* Increased code block timeout to 1min (from 30sec).
* Human readable column labels.

v0.3

* Added dedicated tile to highlight log queries executed in Dashboards (by execution count, total volume) which includes all users who have been executing each query
* Queries executed by code (which utilize App and User variables) now adhere to global timeframe
* Overall log query count and volume charts have dynamic interval (bins) adjusting to global timeframe

v0.2
* Added new variable for price per querying 1 gibibyte (default $0.0035)
* Single figure visualisations show volume and cost per day/week/month in correct unit, and include histogram chart in background

v0.1 â€“ Initial release

##### ToDo

* Add additional section with Davis forecasts if these could add value
* Research DQL optimization to reduce lookups between `dt.system.events` and `dt.system.query_executions`

##### Missing features / bugs

* Can not apply formatting to timestamp field in Top 10 queries (timestamp returned as string)
* Billing events are logged hourly (vs query executions in real time). Due to this timeframe delay, timestamps for recent queries might be missing
* Research why logs app isn't showing up  
* Any queries run by code blocks in Dashboards app are missing `client.application_context` and therefore aren't classified under Dashboards (needs verification)

41.content:
Log queries (`fetch logs`) in Dashboards is convenient way to track log data, but very frequent dashboard reloads by multiple users can increase log query consumption drastically. 

ðŸ’¡ **Optimization opportunity**: for very frequently accessed log dashboards, [extract relevant data from logs during ingest with log metrics](https://docs.dynatrace.com/docs/shortlink/lma-log-dashboards). By replacing log queries with log metric queries, you may increase performance and reduce consumption.

49.query:
fetch dt.system.events
| filter event.kind == "BILLING_USAGE_EVENT" and billing_type == "BILLABLE" and event.type == "Log Management & Analytics - Query" and event.version == "1.0"
| filter in("ALL", $User) OR in(user.email, $User)
| filter in("ALL", $Application) OR in(client.application_context, $Application)
| sort billed_bytes desc
| limit 10
| lookup [
  fetch dt.system.query_executions
],
  sourceField: query_id,
  lookupField: query_id,
  prefix: "executiondata.",
  executionOrder:leftFirst
| fields
    timestamp=toTimestamp(executiondata.timestamp),
    query_string=executiondata.query_string,
    query_volume=toDouble(billed_bytes),
    query_cost = toDouble(billed_bytes)/1024/1024/1024*toDouble($Price),
    User=user.email,
    App=client.application_context
| fieldsRename `Query string`=query_string, `Query volume`=query_volume, `Query cost`=query_cost
| sort `Query volume` desc

50.query:
fetch dt.system.query_executions
| filter status == "SUCCEEDED" and startsWith(query_string, "fetch logs") and client.application_context=="dynatrace.dashboards"
| filter in("ALL", $User) OR in(user.email, $User)
| parse client.source, "DATA 'ui/dashboard/' STRING:dashboard.id"
| summarize {
    single_query_scanned = sum(scanned_bytes),
    dashboards = collectDistinct(dashboard.id)
  }, by:{
    query_id,
    user.email,
    query_string
  }
| sort single_query_scanned desc
| limit 500 // to avoid lookup timeout, we are using only top 500 query executions
| lookup [
  fetch dt.system.events
],
  sourceField: query_id,
  lookupField: query_id,
  prefix: "billing.",
  executionOrder:leftFirst

| filter billing.billing_type == "BILLABLE" // keep only billed queries

| summarize {
    total_consumption = sum(billing.billed_bytes),
    execution_count = count(),
    users = collectDistinct(user.email),
    dashboards = collectDistinct(dashboards)},
  by:{query_string}
| fields query_string, execution_count, total_consumption, total_cost=(total_consumption/1024/1024/1024*toDouble($Price)), Dashboards=arrayFlatten(dashboards), Users=users
| fieldsRename `Query string`=query_string, `Execution count`=execution_count, `Total consumption`=total_consumption, `Total cost`=total_cost
| sort `Total consumption` desc
| limit 50

51.query:
fetch dt.system.events
| filter status == "SUCCEEDED" and startsWith(query_string, "fetch logs")
| filter in("ALL", $User) OR in(user.email, $User)
| filter in("ALL", $Application) OR in(client.application_context, $Application)
| filterOut contains(query_string, "filter")
  OR contains(query_string,"scanLimitGBytes")
  OR contains(query_string,"from:")
  OR contains(query_string, "samplingRatio")
  OR contains(query_string, "limit")
| summarize {executions = count(), query_volume=sum(scanned_bytes)}, by: {query = query_string, user.email, app = client.application_context}
| fieldsAdd query_cost = query_volume/1024/1024/1024*toDouble($Price)
| fields  query, Executions=executions, query_volume, query_cost, User=user.email, App=app
| fieldsRename `Query string`=query, `Query volume`=query_volume, `Query cost`=query_cost
| sort `Query volume` desc, Executions desc, User asc
| limit 50
